const QUESTIONS = [
  { category: "Liquidation Preferences", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "A Series A investor puts in €2M at a 1x non-participating liquidation preference. The company sells for €20M. The investor holds 20% of equity. What does the investor choose?", options: ["Take the €2M preference and forgo any additional upside from the equity conversion", "Convert and take €4M (20% of €20M) because that exceeds the €2M preference", "Take €2M preference PLUS €4M in participation rights simultaneously from the pool", "The investor has no choice — the liquidation preference is triggered automatically"], correct: 1, explanation: "With a 1x non-participating preference, the investor chooses the HIGHER of: (a) their €2M back, or (b) converting to common and taking their 20% = €4M. They'd convert here. This is why non-participating is founder-friendly — at good outcomes, it behaves like common stock.", germanContext: "In German term sheets (Beteiligungsverträge), this is the 'Erlösvorzug ohne Beteiligung'. The BAND/GESSI templates default to 1x non-participating, which is market standard for early-stage DACH deals." },
  { category: "Liquidation Preferences", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "Same deal: €2M invested, 1x participating preference, 20% equity. Company sells for €20M. What does the investor get?", options: ["€4M — just converts to 20% and waives their preference right entirely", "€2M — just the preference, waiving their right to participate in remaining", "€5.6M — gets €2M back plus 20% of remaining €18M in participation", "€6M — receives €2M preference and then a full €4M from participation"], correct: 2, explanation: "Participating preferred = double dip. The investor gets their €2M back FIRST, then participates as if they converted in the remaining €18M → 20% × €18M = €3.6M. Total: €2M + €3.6M = €5.6M. This is significantly more investor-friendly than non-participating.", germanContext: "Called 'Erlösvorzug MIT Beteiligung' in German. Less common in German seed/Series A deals but appears more in later stages or when international VCs lead. HTGF typically does NOT insist on participating preferred." },
  { category: "Liquidation Preferences", difficulty: 3, type: "scenario", question: "You're advising a founder. Two term sheets on the table:\n\nTerm Sheet A: €3M at €12M pre-money, 1x participating preferred\nTerm Sheet B: €3M at €10M pre-money, 1x non-participating preferred\n\nThe company sells for €30M. Which term sheet leaves more for the founders?", options: ["Term Sheet A — the higher headline valuation always wins for founders", "Term Sheet B — non-participating is always better regardless of valuation", "Term Sheet A — the math favors higher valuation at this exit price", "Term Sheet B — founders keep €23.08M versus only €21.6M under A"], correct: 3, explanation: "Term Sheet A: Investor owns 20% (3/15). Participating = €3M + 20%×€27M = €3M + €5.4M = €8.4M. Founders get €21.6M.\n\nTerm Sheet B: Investor owns 23.08% (3/13). Non-participating, so investor converts to 23.08% = €6.92M. Founders get €23.08M.\n\nTerm Sheet B is actually better for founders here! Non-participating at a slightly lower valuation can still beat participating at a higher one. This is exactly why you must model outcomes, not just compare headline valuations.", germanContext: "German founders often fixate on pre-money valuation (Bewertung) as the primary negotiation metric. Experienced DACH VCs know that preference structure can matter more than a €2M valuation difference. Always model exit scenarios in your Beteiligungsvertrag negotiations." },
  { category: "Liquidation Preferences", difficulty: 2, type: "true_false", question: "In a stacked (senior) liquidation preference structure, if a Series B investor has a 2x preference and Series A has a 1x preference, and the exit proceeds are only enough to cover the Series B preference, the Series A investor gets nothing from their preference.", options: ["True", "False"], correct: 0, explanation: "True. In a stacked/senior structure, later rounds get paid first (LIFO). If there's only enough to cover Series B's 2x, Series A's 1x preference is worthless. This is why understanding preference stacking is critical in down-round scenarios. Pari passu (equal ranking) is more founder-friendly.", germanContext: "In German Beteiligungsverträge, the default in BAND templates is often pari passu (gleichrangig), but sophisticated investors may negotiate senior stacking (vorrangig). Pay close attention to §X 'Rangfolge der Erlösverteilung' in the agreement." },
  { category: "Liquidation Preferences", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "What events typically trigger a liquidation preference?", options: ["Only an IPO — the shares convert and the liquidation preference pays out at listing", "Only a trade sale (M&A) — preferences apply exclusively in acquisition exit events", "Any 'deemed liquidation event': trade sale, asset sale, merger, or change of control", "Only voluntary dissolution of the company — the formal winding-down legal process"], correct: 2, explanation: "Liquidation preferences are triggered by 'deemed liquidation events' (fingierte Liquidationsereignisse), which include trade sales, mergers, asset sales, and change-of-control transactions — not just formal liquidation. IPOs typically trigger automatic conversion of preferred to common instead.", germanContext: "In German GmbH structures, this is defined as 'Liquidationsereignis' or 'Exit-Ereignis' in the Gesellschaftsvertrag/Beteiligungsvertrag. Be precise about what constitutes a 'Kontrollwechsel' (change of control) — thresholds matter." },
  { category: "Anti-Dilution", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "An investor has full ratchet anti-dilution protection. They invested €5M at €10/share in Series A. The Series B prices shares at €6/share. What happens?", options: ["The Series A price is retroactively adjusted to €6/share — as if they paid €6", "The investor receives a 40% cash refund on their original investment amount in full", "Nothing happens — anti-dilution only applies to down-rounds below 50% threshold", "The Series A price adjusts to €8/share using the broad-based weighted average formula"], correct: 0, explanation: "Full ratchet is the most aggressive anti-dilution mechanism. It reprices the ENTIRE previous round to the new lower price, regardless of how many new shares are issued. The investor effectively gets credited as if they paid €6/share, receiving additional shares to make up the difference. On €5M, they'd go from 500K shares to ~833K shares.", germanContext: "Full ratchet ('Vollverwässerungsschutz') is quite rare in German deals and generally considered aggressive. Most DACH VCs and the BAND templates use broad-based weighted average. If you see full ratchet in a German term sheet, it's a red flag worth negotiating." },
  { category: "Anti-Dilution", difficulty: 3, type: "multiple_choice", question: "What is the key difference between narrow-based and broad-based weighted average anti-dilution?", options: ["Narrow-based includes all outstanding shares in the formula; broad-based only counts preferred shares outstanding", "Broad-based includes all shares, options, and convertibles in the denominator; narrow-based only preferred", "They produce identical calculations but differ in the exact timing of when the price adjustment triggers", "Narrow-based is always calculated using pre-money figures; broad-based always uses post-money figures instead"], correct: 1, explanation: "The difference is in the denominator of the weighted average formula. Broad-based includes ALL outstanding equity (common, preferred, options, warrants, convertibles) in the share count. Narrow-based only counts preferred shares. Because broad-based has a larger denominator, the price adjustment is smaller → less dilutive to founders. That's why broad-based is more founder-friendly.", germanContext: "German term sheets specify this as 'gewichteter Durchschnitt auf breiter/enger Basis'. The GESSI standard terms and most institutional German VCs (Earlybird, HV Capital, Cherry Ventures) use broad-based weighted average. Always check whether ESOP/VSOP pools are included in the calculation base." },
  { category: "Anti-Dilution", difficulty: 2, type: "true_false", question: "Pay-to-play provisions can override anti-dilution protections — meaning an investor who doesn't participate pro-rata in a down round could lose their anti-dilution rights.", options: ["True", "False"], correct: 0, explanation: "True. Pay-to-play forces investors to participate in future rounds to keep their preferred rights, including anti-dilution. If they don't participate, their preferred shares may convert to common, stripping away both liquidation preferences AND anti-dilution protection.", germanContext: "Pay-to-play ('Nachfinanzierungspflicht' or 'Beteiligungspflicht') is less standardized in German deals compared to the US but is increasingly seen in later-stage German term sheets." },
  { category: "Anti-Dilution", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "Why do anti-dilution clauses exist from the investor's perspective?", options: ["To guarantee a minimum return on the investment regardless of exit outcome", "To protect against overpaying if the company's value decreases in future rounds", "To prevent founders from issuing new shares without getting investor approval first", "To ensure investors maintain board control even as their equity stake gets diluted"], correct: 1, explanation: "Anti-dilution protects investors from economic dilution when a subsequent round prices shares below what they paid. It's price protection, not return guarantee.", germanContext: "In Germany, this is framed in the Beteiligungsvertrag under 'Verwässerungsschutz'. It's important to distinguish from structural dilution (new shares reducing percentage ownership) vs. economic dilution (price per share declining). Anti-dilution addresses the latter." },
  { category: "ESOP & VSOP", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "Why is VSOP (Virtual Stock Option Plan) far more common than a real ESOP in German startups?", options: ["VSOP provides significantly better tax advantages under current German tax legislation", "German GmbH share transfers require notarization, making real equity grants expensive", "German corporate law explicitly prohibits granting real equity directly to employees", "VSOP participation is a mandatory requirement under current German labor law"], correct: 1, explanation: "Every GmbH share transfer requires a notary deed (notarielle Beurkundung) under German law (§15 GmbHG). This costs €500-2000+ per transaction. VSOPs avoid this by granting contractual economic rights that mirror equity without actual share transfers.", germanContext: "This is THE defining feature of German startup equity. Almost every German VC-backed startup uses VSOP instead of real ESOP. The employee receives a contractual claim to a cash payment equivalent to what they'd receive if they held real shares." },
  { category: "ESOP & VSOP", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "Under standard German VSOP terms, what typically happens to a 'Bad Leaver' vs. a 'Good Leaver'?", options: ["Both keep all vested virtual shares regardless of the circumstances of their departure from the company", "Bad Leaver forfeits ALL virtual shares (vested and unvested); Good Leaver keeps vested", "Bad Leaver keeps 50% of their total allocation; Good Leaver keeps the full 100% of their allocation", "Bad Leaver's virtual shares convert to common stock; Good Leaver's shares remain as preferred stock"], correct: 1, explanation: "Standard German VSOP: Bad Leaver (termination for cause, voluntary departure before cliff, breach of contract) → forfeits everything. Good Leaver (termination without cause, death, disability) → keeps all vested virtual shares, forfeits unvested.", germanContext: "In German contracts: 'guter Abgang' vs. 'schlechter Abgang'. Critical detail: German labor courts (Arbeitsgerichte) may scrutinize Bad Leaver clauses for fairness under §307 BGB." },
  { category: "ESOP & VSOP", difficulty: 3, type: "scenario", question: "A CTO has a VSOP with 2% virtual equity, 4-year vesting, 1-year cliff. After 2.5 years, she's terminated without cause (Good Leaver). The company later exits for €50M. The VSOP pool comes after the 1x non-participating liquidation preference of €5M. How much does she receive?", options: ["€1,000,000 (2% of €50M — full virtual equity, ignoring vesting)", "€562,500 (vested portion of 2% applied to €50M minus preference)", "€900,000 (the full 2% applied to the post-preference amount)", "€625,000 (2.5/4 × 2% × (€50M - €5M) — the correct waterfall)"], correct: 3, explanation: "She's a Good Leaver, so she keeps vested virtual shares. Vested = 2.5/4 = 62.5% of her 2% = 1.25% effective virtual equity. VSOP pays after preferences: €50M - €5M = €45M distributable. 1.25% × €45M = €562,500.", germanContext: "Key German VSOP detail: Virtual shares almost always sit BEHIND the liquidation preference waterfall (Erlöswasserfall). The VSOP agreement should clearly define the 'Bezugsgröße' (reference amount)." },
  { category: "ESOP & VSOP", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "What was the key change in German tax law (§19a EStG, effective 2021/2024) regarding employee equity in startups?", options: ["Virtual shares and VSOP payouts are now completely exempt from income taxation", "Employee equity gains are now taxed at a flat 15% rate across all qualifying startups", "Tax on equity/virtual share grants can be deferred — no more 'dry income' taxation", "All VSOP payouts are now treated as capital gains at 26.375% instead of income"], correct: 2, explanation: "The §19a EStG reform allows tax deferral on equity participation in qualifying startups, solving the 'dry income' problem.", germanContext: "§19a EStG was expanded in 2024 (Zukunftsfinanzierungsgesetz). However, VSOP payouts remain taxed as employment income at up to ~45%, not as capital gains (~26.375%). This is the single biggest structural disadvantage for German startup employees vs. US counterparts." },
  { category: "ESOP & VSOP", difficulty: 1, type: "true_false", question: "In a standard German VSOP, the employee becomes a legal shareholder (Gesellschafter) of the GmbH.", options: ["True", "False"], correct: 1, explanation: "False. In a VSOP, the employee has a purely contractual claim — they are NOT a Gesellschafter. They don't appear in the Handelsregister, have no voting rights, and no standing at the Gesellschafterversammlung.", germanContext: "A VSOP participant has fewer protections than a real shareholder. Some VSOP agreements grant limited information rights, but these are contractual, not statutory." },
  { category: "Exit & Transfer Rights", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "What is a Right of First Refusal (ROFR / Vorkaufsrecht) in a VC context?", options: ["The right to be the first investor in the next funding round at a preferred price", "The right to match any third-party offer to buy shares before the sale proceeds", "The right to refuse any new investor from joining the company's cap table", "The right to sell your own shares before any other shareholder can sell"], correct: 1, explanation: "ROFR gives existing shareholders the right to purchase shares on the same terms as a third-party buyer before the selling shareholder can complete the sale.", germanContext: "In German: 'Vorkaufsrecht'. Important: German law (§463 BGB) has statutory pre-emption rights, but VC agreements create contractual Vorkaufsrechte. Note the distinction from Bezugsrecht (pre-emption on NEW share issuances)." },
  { category: "Exit & Transfer Rights", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "Tag-Along rights (Mitverkaufsrecht) protect which party and how?", options: ["They protect investors by letting them force founders to sell their shares in any exit", "They protect minority shareholders by letting them join a sale on the same terms", "They protect founders by contractually preventing investors from selling any shares", "They protect the company by requiring a commission payment on all secondary sales"], correct: 1, explanation: "Tag-along protects minority shareholders by giving them the right to 'tag along' and sell their shares on the same price and terms when a majority shareholder sells.", germanContext: "In German: 'Mitverkaufsrecht' or 'Mitveräußerungsrecht'. Standard clause in every German Beteiligungsvertrag. The BAND template includes this as a default minority protection." },
  { category: "Exit & Transfer Rights", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "Drag-Along rights (Mitveräußerungspflicht) allow what?", options: ["Any shareholder can unilaterally force all other shareholders to sell at any time", "A defined majority can force ALL shareholders to sell to a buyer on same terms", "Founders can drag investors into participating in additional future funding rounds", "The advisory board can unilaterally force an IPO without any shareholder vote"], correct: 1, explanation: "Drag-along forces dissenting shareholders to sell when a qualifying majority agrees to an exit. This prevents a small minority from blocking an acquisition.", germanContext: "In German: 'Mitveräußerungspflicht'. BAND templates often set the threshold at 75% by capital AND investor majority consent. The threshold and consent mechanics are among the most negotiated clauses in German Beteiligungsverträge." },
  { category: "Exit & Transfer Rights", difficulty: 3, type: "scenario", question: "A buyer offers €40M. The drag-along requires 75% approval. Shareholders: Founder (40%), Series A VC (30%), Series B VC (20%), Angels (10%). The Founder and Series B want to sell. Series A and Angels don't. Can the drag-along be triggered?", options: ["Yes — Founder + Series B = 60%, which is sufficient", "No — 60% is below the 75% threshold required", "Yes — the founder always has drag-along rights", "It depends on the Series A VC's blocking right"], correct: 1, explanation: "60% is below the 75% drag-along threshold. The drag cannot be triggered. This illustrates why drag thresholds matter enormously.", germanContext: "In German GmbH law, amendments to the Gesellschaftsvertrag require 75% by default (§53 GmbHG). Savvy German VCs negotiate specific Zustimmungsvorbehalte that can block exits regardless of the drag threshold." },
  { category: "Exit & Transfer Rights", difficulty: 1, type: "true_false", question: "A No-Shop clause prevents the company from soliciting or negotiating with other potential investors/buyers during a defined exclusivity period.", options: ["True", "False"], correct: 0, explanation: "True. No-shop gives the lead investor an exclusivity window (typically 4-8 weeks) where the company cannot shop the deal to competitors.", germanContext: "In German: 'Exklusivitätsvereinbarung'. Standard in German term sheets. Typical period: 4-6 weeks for early-stage, up to 8-12 weeks for larger deals." },
  { category: "Convertible Instruments", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "What is a Wandeldarlehen in the German startup context?", options: ["A government subsidy program specifically designed to support early-stage startups in Germany", "A convertible loan that converts into equity at a future financing round with a discount", "A type of preferred share class with special conversion rights that are attached to it", "A bridge loan instrument that must always be repaid in full cash amount at maturity"], correct: 1, explanation: "A Wandeldarlehen (convertible loan) is the German equivalent of a convertible note. The investor lends money, and instead of repayment, the loan converts into equity at the next qualified financing round.", germanContext: "Wandeldarlehen are extremely popular in German pre-seed and seed deals. Key difference from US SAFEs: Wandeldarlehen are actual debt instruments and accrue interest (usually 1-5%)." },
  { category: "Convertible Instruments", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "A Wandeldarlehen has a €5M valuation cap and a 20% discount. The Series A prices the company at €8M pre-money. At what effective valuation does the convertible convert?", options: ["€8M — the Series A price applies directly without any adjustments", "€6.4M — the 20% discount on €8M gives this effective conversion price", "€5M — the cap applies because it is lower than discounted price", "€4M — you apply the 20% discount on top of the €5M valuation cap"], correct: 2, explanation: "The conversion uses the MORE favorable (lower) of: (a) the discounted price: €8M × 0.8 = €6.4M, or (b) the valuation cap: €5M. Since €5M < €6.4M, the cap applies. The discount and cap don't stack — you take whichever is lower.", germanContext: "In German Wandeldarlehen: the cap is 'Bewertungsobergrenze' and discount is 'Abschlag/Rabatt'. Important: some poorly drafted convertible loans accidentally allow stacking (cap AND discount)." },
  { category: "Convertible Instruments", difficulty: 3, type: "multiple_choice", question: "What is a key structural difference between a US SAFE and a German Wandeldarlehen?", options: ["SAFEs include valuation caps while Wandeldarlehen do not support caps at all in practice", "Wandeldarlehen are debt with interest accrual and maturity; SAFEs are not debt at all", "SAFEs convert on any equity round; Wandeldarlehen only convert upon an IPO or listing", "There is no meaningful structural difference between these two convertible instruments"], correct: 1, explanation: "A SAFE is NOT debt — no interest, no maturity, no repayment obligation. A Wandeldarlehen IS a loan — it accrues interest, has a maturity date, and creates a repayment obligation if conversion isn't triggered.", germanContext: "Because a Wandeldarlehen is debt, the investor becomes a creditor. In insolvency (Insolvenzverfahren), creditors rank ahead of equity holders. Some German lawyers have begun drafting 'SAFE-like' instruments, but their legal treatment remains debated." },
  { category: "Convertible Instruments", difficulty: 2, type: "true_false", question: "If a Wandeldarlehen reaches maturity without a qualified financing event, the investor can demand cash repayment of the loan plus accrued interest.", options: ["True", "False"], correct: 0, explanation: "True — technically. Since a Wandeldarlehen is a loan, the lender has a legal right to demand repayment at maturity. In practice, this is rarely enforced, but the legal right creates leverage.", germanContext: "Experienced founders negotiate automatic conversion at maturity at the cap valuation, or a long maturity (24-36 months). The maturity date is 'Fälligkeitsdatum' or 'Laufzeit'." },
  { category: "Governance & Control", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "Which is typically a protective provision (Zustimmungsvorbehalt) giving investors veto power in a German Beteiligungsvertrag?", options: ["Hiring any new employee at any level across the entire organization requires approval", "Changing the company's social media strategy or overall marketing approach for campaigns", "Issuing new shares, taking on debt above a threshold, or selling the company outright", "Setting individual employee salaries and determining their annual bonus allocations"], correct: 2, explanation: "Protective provisions give investors veto rights over major company decisions regardless of their equity percentage.", germanContext: "In German GmbH law: 'Zustimmungsvorbehalte' or 'Negativkatalog'. The GESSI standard template lists ~15-20 veto matters. Key German-specific items: granting of Prokura, changes to the Geschäftsordnung." },
  { category: "Governance & Control", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "In a German GmbH, who has the ultimate decision-making authority?", options: ["The CEO (Geschäftsführer) who runs all day-to-day operations of the company", "The Board of Directors (Aufsichtsrat) that oversees and monitors management", "The Shareholder Meeting (Gesellschafterversammlung) as the supreme body", "The investors with the most shares based on their total equity stake"], correct: 2, explanation: "In a German GmbH the Gesellschafterversammlung is the highest decision-making body — unlike US corporate law where the board is supreme.", germanContext: "This is fundamental to German VC governance. VCs exercise control through protective provisions, qualified majority requirements, and sometimes a Beirat with defined competencies." },
  { category: "Governance & Control", difficulty: 2, type: "scenario", question: "A startup has a Beirat with 3 seats: 1 founder, 1 Series A investor, 1 independent. The founder wants to hire a CFO at €180K. The Beteiligungsvertrag requires Beirat approval for exec hires above €150K. The investor disagrees. What happens?", options: ["The founder hires anyway — the Beirat is purely advisory in nature here", "Blocked — the Beirat requires unanimity for all executive hiring decisions", "Goes to a vote: 2 vs 1, approved if independent agrees with founder", "The Gesellschafterversammlung must formally decide on this hiring matter"], correct: 2, explanation: "The Beirat votes by simple majority (unless specified otherwise). With 3 seats, a 2-1 vote is decisive. The independent becomes the swing vote.", germanContext: "A Beirat in a German GmbH is NOT an Aufsichtsrat — it's contractually created. German VCs often insist on Beirat structures to replicate US-style board governance within the GmbH framework." },
  { category: "Governance & Control", difficulty: 3, type: "true_false", question: "In a German GmbH, investors can include a clause allowing them to dismiss the Geschäftsführer (CEO) without the standard 75% shareholder vote.", options: ["True", "False"], correct: 0, explanation: "True. German GmbH law allows significant flexibility in structuring dismissal rights. The Gesellschaftsvertrag can modify the default under §38 GmbHG.", germanContext: "Founders should negotiate 'wichtiger Grund' (cause) requirements, notice periods, and whether their own shares count in the vote." },
  { category: "Valuation & Economics", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "A VC offers €3M on a €9M pre-money valuation. What is the post-money valuation and VC ownership?", options: ["Post-money: €12M. VC owns 25%", "Post-money: €9M. VC owns 33%", "Post-money: €12M. VC owns 33%", "Post-money: €9M. VC owns 25%"], correct: 0, explanation: "Post-money = Pre-money + Investment = €9M + €3M = €12M. VC ownership = €3M / €12M = 25%.", germanContext: "A common trap in German term sheets: the ESOP/VSOP pool. If the term sheet says '€9M pre-money including a 10% ESOP pool', the effective pre-money for existing shareholders is only ~€8.1M. This is the 'Option Pool Shuffle'." },
  { category: "Valuation & Economics", difficulty: 2, type: "scenario", question: "Term sheet says: '€4M investment at €12M pre-money, with a 15% ESOP pool to be created pre-closing from the pre-money.' What is the founder's effective pre-money valuation?", options: ["€12M — the pool is entirely the investors' problem to absorb", "€10.2M — the 15% pool reduces the effective pre-money valuation", "€12M minus €4M = €8M — simple subtraction of the investment", "€13.6M — the pool actually adds to the overall company valuation"], correct: 1, explanation: "The option pool shuffle: the 15% pool dilutes ONLY existing shareholders (founders). Effective pre-money for founders: €12M × (1 - 0.15) = €10.2M.", germanContext: "Very common in German deals. Founders should negotiate for a smaller pool sized to actual 18-24 month hiring needs, not a blanket 15-20%." },
  { category: "Valuation & Economics", difficulty: 3, type: "multiple_choice", question: "Company raised: Seed (€1M at €4M pre), Series A (€4M at €16M pre), Series B (€10M at €40M pre). All 1x non-participating, pari passu. Company sells for €25M. How are proceeds distributed?", options: ["Each gets their money back first, then remaining is split by equity percentage", "All investors convert to common — everything is split by equity percentage only", "Series B is paid first (as the most senior), then Series A, then Seed in order", "Each investor independently chooses the better of preference or conversion"], correct: 3, explanation: "With non-participating preferred, each investor independently decides. Series B (20%) would get €5M converting but has €10M preference → takes preference. Series A converts for €5M (beats €4M preference). Seed converts for €5M (beats €1M preference).", germanContext: "This waterfall analysis ('Erlöswasserfall') is critical in German M&A scenarios. Use a waterfall model spreadsheet — don't try this in your head during a negotiation." },
  { category: "Pre-emption & Pro-rata", difficulty: 1, type: "multiple_choice", question: "What is a pre-emption right (Bezugsrecht) in the context of a new funding round?", options: ["The right to buy shares at a significant discount to the current round price", "The right to invest in a new round to maintain your ownership percentage", "The right to veto a new funding round if you disagree with the pricing terms", "The right to approve or reject the lead investor chosen for the funding round"], correct: 1, explanation: "Pre-emption rights allow existing shareholders to participate in a new share issuance to maintain their percentage ownership.", germanContext: "In German GmbH law: §§ 53/55 GmbHG don't explicitly grant Bezugsrechte (unlike §186 AktG for AGs), so they must be contractually agreed." },
  { category: "Pre-emption & Pro-rata", difficulty: 2, type: "true_false", question: "'Super pro-rata' rights allow an investor to invest MORE than their current ownership percentage in a new round.", options: ["True", "False"], correct: 0, explanation: "True. Super pro-rata lets the investor oversubscribe relative to their ownership, potentially increasing their stake disproportionately.", germanContext: "In German: 'Überproportionales Bezugsrecht'. Relatively rare in standard German seed/Series A deals. The BAND template does not include super pro-rata as a default." },
  { category: "Advanced Scenarios", difficulty: 3, type: "scenario", question: "A German startup is raising a Series B. The Series A lead has a 20% pro-rata right, ROFR on secondary sales, and investor consent for new share issuances. The Series B lead wants to buy 5% from an angel AND lead an €8M primary round. What approvals are needed?", options: ["Just the Gesellschafterversammlung vote for the capital increase alone is needed", "Series A consent for new shares + ROFR for secondary + Gesellschafterversammlung", "Only the secondary ROFR needs to be processed for the angel's share sale", "No special approvals are needed — only standard transaction procedures apply"], correct: 1, explanation: "Three mechanics are triggered: (1) New share issuance needs Series A consent + Gesellschafterversammlung + notarized Satzungsänderung. (2) The angel's secondary sale triggers ROFR. (3) Series A may exercise pro-rata in the primary round.", germanContext: "German deal closings are more procedurally complex than US closings because of mandatory notarization (§53 GmbHG). Budget 4-6 weeks from signed term sheet to closing." },
  { category: "Advanced Scenarios", difficulty: 3, type: "scenario", question: "A founder holds 60% of a German GmbH. They want to do a down-round. The Series A investor has broad-based weighted average anti-dilution and 1x participating preferred. What are the cascading effects?", options: ["Nothing special — it is just a new round priced at a lower valuation than the previous one was", "Anti-dilution adjusts price → more shares → more dilution → larger preference base → shifts", "Only the anti-dilution mechanism kicks in — nothing else in the overall structure changes at all", "The founder's shares get automatically repriced to match the new lower valuation of the company"], correct: 1, explanation: "Down-rounds create cascading effects: anti-dilution triggers → more Series A shares → extra founder dilution → larger participating preference base → VSOP holders diluted extra. A 30% down-round can shift 10-15% additional economics to Series A.", germanContext: "Down-rounds in German startups are particularly complex: the Satzungsänderung requires 75% approval, Bezugsrechte must be excluded, and the Geschäftsführer may face personal liability (§ 64 GmbHG / § 15b InsO)." },
  { category: "Advanced Scenarios", difficulty: 2, type: "multiple_choice", question: "What is 'Reverse Vesting' and why is it standard in German VC deals?", options: ["Investors gradually vest into their shares over time based on their ongoing involvement", "Founders receive all shares upfront but are subject to repurchase if leaving early", "VSOP holders vest in reverse chronological order from the most recent to the earliest", "The company can claw back investor shares if certain performance milestones are not met"], correct: 1, explanation: "Reverse vesting means founders already own their shares but agree to a repurchase right that expires over time (typically 4 years, 1-year cliff).", germanContext: "In German: 'Rückübertragungspflicht'. Virtually every German VC requires this. The repurchase involves a notarized share transfer (Anteilsabtretung)." },
];

